The '''1942 Ruislip Wellington accident''' occurred on the 18 October 1942 when a [[Royal Air Force]] twin-engined [[Vickers Wellington]] 1c bomber crashed close to [[South Ruislip station]] while on approach to [[RAF Northolt]], all 15 on-board and six on the ground (including four children) were killed.<ref name="asn">{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=66571|title=18-OCT-1942 Vickers Wellington Mk 1C T2564|accessdate=30 December 2013|publisher=Aviation Safety Network}}</ref>
==Accident== The Vickers Wellington was operated by [[No. 311 Squadron RAF|No. 311 Squadron]] of the Royal Air Force, 311 was a Czechoslovakian-manned [[Coastal Command]] squadron based at [[RAF Talbenny]] in Pembrokeshire, Wales. Following successful operation by the squadron they were invited to London for a de-brief.<ref>{{cite book |last=Osolsobě |first=Jiří |date=1990 |title=Zbylo nás devět |language=Czech |edition=2nd |location=Praha |publisher=Naše vojsko |isbn=80-206-0207-0 |pages=163-166}}</ref> On 18 October 1942 Wellington [[United Kingdom military aircraft serials|serial number]] ''T2564'' was being flown by Pilot Officer František Bulis with a crew of six and nine passengers when, on approach to RAF Northolt the Wellington crashed near South Ruislip railway station at 16:08 and burst into flames.<ref name="times49370">"18 Killed In Air Accident." Times [London, England] 19 Oct. 1942: 4. The Times Digital Archive. Web. 30 Dec. 2013.</ref>
All the crew and passengers (all Czechoslovaks apart from a Belgian technical officer) were killed, also killed on the ground were two women each with two children.<ref name="times49371">"Nineteen Dead In Air Accident." Times [London, England] 20 Oct. 1942: 2. The Times Digital Archive. Web. 30 Dec. 2013.</ref> All but one of the crew were buried at Brooklands Military Cemetery where a memorial to them stands. The two sisters and children were buried at [[Brockenhurst]], Hampshire.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Western Gazette|date=30 October 1942|title=Ruislip 'Plane Crash Victims - Mothers and Children Buried}}</ref>
==Inquest== As well as a service inquiry an inquest was also held into the deaths of the two sisters and their four children at Uxbridge, the aircraft was deemed to have been serviceable and was not overloaded.<ref name="times49275" /> A witness at Northolt said it was flying quite normally: "It made a quarter circle, gradually losing height. Then it appeared to lose height rather more quickly and disappeared behind some houses".<ref name="times49275" /> The coroner recorded a verdict of accidental death.<ref name="times49275">"Northolt Air Accident." Times [London, England] 24 Oct. 1942: 2. The Times Digital Archive. Web. 30 Dec. 2013.</ref>
